05685nam a22006375i 9780774855785DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20082007xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748557857 a10.59962/97807748557852doi  a(DE-B1597)661801  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aE98.F39bM97 2007eb 7aSOC0210002bisacsh04a305.800aMyth and Memory :bStories of Indigenous-European Contact /ced. by John Sutton Lutz. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Myth Understandings; or First Contact, Over and Over Again -- tClose Encounters of the First Kind -- tFirst Contact as a Spiritual Performance: Encounters on the North American West Coast -- tReflections on Indigenous History and Memory: Reconstructing and Reconsidering Contact -- tPoking Fun: Humour and Power in Kaska Contact Narratives -- tHerbert Spencer, Paul Kane, and the Making of “The Chinook” -- tPerforming Paradox: Narrativity and the Lost Colony of Roanoke -- tStories from the Margins: Toward a More Inclusive British Columbia Historiography -- tWhen the White Kawau Flies -- tThe Interpreter as Contact Point: Avoiding Collisions in Tlingit America -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe moment of contact between two peoples, two alien societies, marks the opening of an epoch and the joining of histories. What if it had happened differently? The stories that indigenous peoples and Europeans tell about their first encounters with one another are enormously valuable historical records, but their relevance extends beyond the past. Settler populations and indigenous peoples the world over are engaged in negotiations over legitimacy, power, and rights. These struggles cannot be dissociated from written and oral accounts of "contact" moments, which not only shape our collective sense of history but also guide our understanding of current events. For all their importance, contact stories have not been systematically or critically evaluated as a genre. Myth and Memory explores the narratives of indigenous and newcomer populations from New Zealand and across North America, from the Lost Colony of Roanoke on the Atlantic seaboard of the United States to the Pacific Northwest and as far as Sitka, Alaska. It illustrates how indigenous and explorer accounts of the same meetings reflect fundamentally different systems of thought, and focuses on the cultural misunderstandings embedded in these stories. The contributors discuss the contemporary relevance, production, and performance of Aboriginal and European contact narratives, and introduce new tools for interpreting the genre. They argue that we are still in the contact zone, striving to understand the meaning of contact and the relationship between indigenous and settler populations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aBinney, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlson, Keith Thor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChamberlin, J. Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDauenhauer, Nora Marks, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDauenhauer, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarkin, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLutz, John Sutton, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLutz